The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Panel to work on WTO bids
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Panel to work on WTO bids
          SUBRAT DAS                              
	Bhubaneswar, June 15: The state government has streamlined its machinery to counter challenges and harness opportunities thrown open by the World Trade Organisation (WTO) system.         
	A high-power WTO preparedness monitoring committee headed by the chief secretary has been constituted and a WTO Cell has been put in place in the Industrial Promotion and Investment Corporation Limited (Ipicol), the nodal agency for industrial promotion, a senior officer in the industries department told The Telegraph.         
	The monitoring committee has been mandated to study and analyse agreement and legislation of the WTO and recommend the measures to the government for protecting and promoting the interests of the state, he said.         
	The body will also monitor the degree of preparedness of government departments and agencies to meet challenges and opportunities emanating out of the WTO.         
	On the other hand, the body would aid and advise the government regarding the WTO system and suggest policies and programmes that may be implemented to develop industry, agriculture and services within the WTO framework.         
	It will deliberate and settle inter-departmental issues pertaining to and emanating out of the WTO.         
	Similarly, the WTO cell, headed by managing director of Ipicol, will create awareness and build capacities of the industries, entrepreneurs, and officers.         
	The cell would be assigned to gather information on legislation and agreements under the WTO and disseminating information.         
	It would evaluate the impact of agreements and legislations under the WTO on the states economy and growth in the wake of challenges, formulation of a WTO strategy document for the industry, agriculture and services sectors.         
	The states WTO cell would manned by a general manager with two experts, who will develop a database on trade and WTO and provide WTO-related consultancy services.                                                                                                                                                                         
